'''Chelsea Football Club''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|tʃ|ɛ|l|s|iː}} is an English [[Association football|football]] club based in [[Fulham]], London. Founded in 1905, they play in the [[Premier League]] and have spent most of their history in the top tier of English football. Their home ground is the 41,837-seat<ref name="capacity"/> [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] stadium, where they have played since their establishment.

Chelsea had their first major success in [[1954–55 Chelsea F.C. season|1955]], when they won the league championship, and won various cup competitions during the 1960s, 1970s, 1990s and 2000s. The club has enjoyed its greatest period of success in the past two decades, winning 15 major trophies since 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/HistoryTrophiesIndex/0,,10268,00.html |title=Trophy Cabinet |publisher=Chelsea F.C. official website |accessdate=20 May 2012 }}</ref>
Domestically, Chelsea have won four [[List of English football champions#Total titles won|league titles]], seven [[FA Cup]]s, four [[Football League Cup|League Cups]] and four [[FA Community Shield]]s, while in continental competitions they have won two [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]]s, one [[UEFA Super Cup]], one [[UEFA Europa League]] and one [[UEFA Champions League]]. Chelsea are the only London club to win the UEFA Champions League,<ref name="Chelsea win breaks London duck">{{cite news |title=Chelsea win breaks London duck |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1798274.html#chelseas+capital+gains |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=20 May 2012 |accessdate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> one of [[UEFA club competition records#List of teams to have won the three main European club competitions|four clubs]], and the only British club, to have won all three main [[UEFA]] club competitions, and also the first club to hold two major European titles simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1449255/ivanovic-goal-wins-europa-league-chelsea?cc=5901 |title=Chelsea wins Europa on Ivanovic header |publisher=ESPNFC |date=16 May 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1947872.html |title=Chelsea join illustrious trio |publisher=Uefa.com |accessdate=17 May 2013 }}</ref>

Chelsea's regular [[Kit (association football)|kit]] colours are royal blue shirts and shorts with white socks. The club's crest has been changed several times in attempts to re-brand the club and modernise its image. The current crest, featuring a ceremonial lion rampant regardant holding a staff, is a modification of the one introduced in the early 1950s.<ref name="new crest">{{cite news |title=Chelsea centenary crest unveiled |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4008257.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=12 November 2004 |accessdate=2 January 2007 }}</ref> The club has sustained the fifth highest average all-time attendance in [[Football in England|English football]].<ref name="attendance">{{cite web | url=http://nufc.com/2011-12html/attendance-all-time.html | title=All Time League Attendance Records | accessdate=8 November 2013 |date=22 May 2011 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120111003541/http://nufc.com/2011-12html/attendance-all-time.html |archivedate=11 January 2012}}</ref> Their average home gate for the [[2012–13 in English football|2012–13 season]] was 41,462, the sixth highest in the [[Premier League]].<ref name="12/13 attendances">{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerstats.com/attendance.asp?league=england|title=Home attendance|publisher=Soccerstats.com|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> Since July 2003, Chelsea have been owned by Russian billionaire [[Roman Abramovich]].<ref name="takeover">{{cite news |title=Russian businessman buys Chelsea |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3036838.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 July 2003 |accessdate=11 February 2007 }}</ref>
In April 2013 it was ranked by [[Forbes|Forbes Magazine]] as the [[Forbes' list of the most valuable football clubs|seventh most valuable football club in the world]], at £588&nbsp;million ($901&nbsp;million), an increase of 18% from the previous year.<ref name="Forbes List">{{cite web |first=Peter J. |last=Schwartz |title=Manchester United Again The World's Most Valuable Soccer Team |url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/mikeozanian/2012/04/18/manchester-united-again-the-worlds-most-valuable-soccer-team/ |work=Forbes Magazine |date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=5 May 2012 }}</ref><ref name="BBC - Forbes">{{cite news |title=Manchester United still the world's richest football club – Forbes |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17769654 |work=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=19 April 2012 |accessdate=5 May 2012 }}</ref>

==History==
{{Main|History of Chelsea F.C.}}
[[File:Chelsea Team 1905.jpg|thumb|250 px|The [[History of Chelsea F.C.|first Chelsea team]] in September 1905]]

In 1904, [[Gus Mears]] acquired the [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] athletics stadium with the aim of turning it into a football ground. An offer to lease it to nearby [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] was turned down, so Mears opted to found his own club to use the stadium. As there was already a team named Fulham in the borough, the name of the adjacent borough of [[Metropolitan Borough of Chelsea|Chelsea]] was chosen for the new club; names like ''Kensington FC'', ''Stamford Bridge FC'' and ''London FC'' were also considered.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=55}}</ref> Chelsea were founded on 10 March 1905 at The Rising Sun pub (now The Butcher's Hook),<ref name="teamhistory"/> opposite the present-day main entrance to the ground on [[Fulham Road]], and were elected to the Football League shortly afterwards.

The club won promotion to the First Division in their second season, and yo-yoed between the First and Second Divisions in their early years. They reached the [[1915 FA Cup Final]], where they lost to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] at Old Trafford, and finished 3rd in the First Division in 1920, the club's best league campaign to that point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/TeamHistory/0,,10268~1800262,00.html|title=Team History – 1905–29 |publisher=Chelsea F.C. official website|accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Chelsea attracted large crowds<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/TeamHistory/0,,10268~910883,00.html|title=Between the Wars – Big Names and Big Crowds|publisher=Chelsea F.C. official website|accessdate=7 May 2012|archiveurl=http://archive.is/1kUL|archivedate=2012-06-30}}</ref> and had a reputation for signing big-name players,<ref name="glanville">{{cite news | date=10 January 2004 | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article992039.ece | title=Little sign of change for Chelsea and their impossible dreams |work=The Times |location=UK| accessdate=15 March 2009 | author=[[Brian Glanville]]}} {{registration required}}</ref> but success continued to elude the club in the inter-war years.

Former [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and England centre-forward [[Ted Drake]] became manager in 1952 and proceeded to modernise the club. He removed the club's [[Chelsea pensioner]] crest, improved the youth set-up and training regime, rebuilt the side with shrewd signings from the lower divisions and amateur leagues, and led Chelsea to their first major trophy success – the League championship – in [[1954–55 Chelsea F.C. season|1954–55]]. The following season saw UEFA create the [[UEFA Champions League|European Champions' Cup]], but after objections from [[The Football League]] and the [[The Football Association|FA]] Chelsea were persuaded to withdraw from the competition before it started.<ref>{{cite news | date=27 April 2005 | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,762-1586242,00.html | title=The great Chelsea surrender |work=The Times |location=UK | accessdate=29 December 2006 |author=[[Brian Glanville]] }}</ref> Chelsea failed to build on this success, and spent the remainder of the 1950s in mid-table. Drake was dismissed in 1961 and replaced by player-coach [[Tommy Docherty]].

[[File:Chelsea FC League Performance 1906-2008.PNG|thumb|left|Chart showing the progress of Chelsea's league finishes from 1905 to 1906 season to [[2007–08 Premier League|2007–08 season]]]]

Docherty built a new team around the group of talented young players emerging from the club's youth set-up and Chelsea challenged for honours throughout the 1960s, enduring several near-misses. They were on course for a treble of League, FA Cup and League Cup going into the final stages of the 1964–65 season, winning the League Cup but faltering late on in the other two.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill, Rick | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography – The Definitive Story of the First 100 Years| publisher=Headline Book Publishing Ltd| year=2006| isbn=978-0-7553-1466-9 | page=196}}</ref> In three seasons the side were beaten in three major semi-finals and were FA Cup runners-up. Under Docherty's successor, [[Dave Sexton]], Chelsea won the [[1970 FA Cup Final|FA Cup in 1970]], beating [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] 2–1 in a final replay. Chelsea took their first European honour, a [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] triumph, the following year, with another replayed win, this time over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in Athens.

The late 1970s through to the 1980s was a turbulent period for Chelsea. An ambitious redevelopment of Stamford Bridge threatened the financial stability of the club,<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=84–87}}</ref> star players were sold and the team were relegated. Further problems were caused by a notorious [[hooliganism|hooligan]] element among the support, which was to plague the club throughout the decade.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=143–157}}</ref> In 1982, Chelsea were, at the nadir of their fortunes, acquired by [[Ken Bates]] for the nominal sum of £1, although by now the Stamford Bridge freehold had been sold to property developers, meaning the club faced losing their home.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=89–90}}</ref> On the pitch, the team had fared little better, coming close to relegation to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] for the first time, but in 1983 manager [[John Neal (footballer)|John Neal]] put together an impressive new team for minimal outlay. Chelsea won the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] title in 1983–84 and established themselves in the top division, before being relegated again in 1988. The club bounced back immediately by winning the Second Division championship in 1988–89.

[[File:Chelsea UCL Winners 2012.jpg|thumb|250px|Chelsea players celebrate their first [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final|UEFA Champions League title]] against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]]]

After a long-running legal battle, Bates reunited the stadium freehold with the club in 1992 by doing a deal with the banks of the property developers, who had been bankrupted by a market crash.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=90–91}}</ref> Chelsea's form in the new Premier League was unconvincing, although they did reach the [[1994 FA Cup Final]] with [[Glenn Hoddle]]. It was not until the appointment of [[Ruud Gullit]] as player-manager in 1996 that their fortunes changed. He added several top international players to the side, as the club [[1997 FA Cup Final|won the FA Cup in 1997]] and established themselves as one of England's top sides again. Gullit was replaced by [[Gianluca Vialli]], who led the team to victory in the [[1998 Football League Cup Final|League Cup Final]], the [[1998 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup Final|UEFA Cup Winners' Cup Final]] and the [[1998 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]] in 1998, the [[2000 FA Cup Final|FA Cup in 2000]] and their first appearance in the [[UEFA Champions League]]. Vialli was sacked in favour of [[Claudio Ranieri]], who guided Chelsea to the [[2002 FA Cup Final]] and Champions League qualification in 2002–03.

In June 2003, Bates sold Chelsea to Russian billionaire [[Roman Abramovich]] for £140&nbsp;million.<ref name="takeover"/> Over £100&nbsp;million was spent on new players, but Ranieri was unable to deliver any trophies,<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea sack Ranieri |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/3742477.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=1 June 2004 |accessdate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> and was replaced by [[José Mourinho]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea appoint Mourinho |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/3765263.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 June 2004 |accessdate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> Under Mourinho, Chelsea became the fifth English team to win back-to-back league championships since the Second World War ([[2004–05 FA Premier League|2004–05]] and [[2005–06 FA Premier League|2005–06]]),<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.sportinglife.com/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/06/03/12/SOCCER_Chelsea.html&TEAMHD=soccer | title=Terry Eyes Back-to-Back Titles | publisher=Sporting Life | accessdate=22 January 2007 | author=Matt Barlow|date=12 March 2006 }}</ref> in addition to winning an FA Cup ([[2007 FA Cup Final|2007]]) and two League Cups ([[2005 Football League Cup Final|2005]] and [[2007 Football League Cup Final|2007]]). Mourinho was replaced by [[Avram Grant]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea name Grant as new manager |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/7004083.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 September 2007 |accessdate=21 September 2007 }}</ref> who led the club to their [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|first UEFA Champions League final]], which they lost on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]] to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].

In 2009, [[Guus Hiddink]] guided Chelsea to another [[2009 FA Cup Final|FA Cup success]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea 2–1 Everton |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/8060989.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=30 May 2009 |accessdate=1 June 2009 }}</ref> and in [[2009–10 in English football|2009–10]], his successor [[Carlo Ancelotti]] led them to their first [[2009–10 Premier League|league]] and [[2010 FA Cup Final|FA Cup]] "[[Double (association football)|Double]]", becoming the first English top-flight club to score 100 league goals in a season since [[1962–63 in English football|1963]].<ref name="Wigan80">{{cite news |title=Chelsea 8–0 Wigan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8663686.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=9 May 2010 |accessdate=16 May 2010 }}</ref> In 2012 caretaker manager [[Roberto Di Matteo]] led Chelsea to their seventh [[2012 FA Cup Final|FA Cup]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea 2–1 Liverpool |first=Phil |last=McNulty |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17878435 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 May 2012 |accessdate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> and their first [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final|UEFA Champions League title]], beating [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] 4–3 on penalties,<ref name="final2012">{{cite news |title=Bayern Munich 1–1 Chelsea (aet, 4–3 pens) |first=Phil |last=McNulty |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18044385 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=19 May 2012 |accessdate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> the first London club to win the trophy.<ref name="final2012"/>  A year later Chelsea won the [[2013 UEFA Europa League Final|UEFA Europa League]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Benfica 1-2 Chelsea |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22445388 |work=BBC |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 May 2013 |accessdate=15 May 2013 }}</ref> becoming the first club to hold two major European titles simultaneously and one of [[UEFA club competition records#List of teams to have won the three main European club competitions|four clubs]], and the only British club, to have won all three of [[UEFA]]'s major club competitions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea claim last-gasp Europa League triumph |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hvKoBXa2illaBsY08MgEqORVvLkQ?docId=CNG.ed0a8f81bd5745978904d66a17caa38a.721 |work=AFP |publisher=AFP |date=15 May 2013 |accessdate=03 August 2013 }}</ref>

==Stadium==
{{Main|Stamford Bridge (stadium)}}
{{Infobox stadium
| stadium_name = Stamford Bridge
| nickname = The Bridge
| image =    [[File:Stamford Bridge - West Stand.jpg|250px]]
| location = [[Fulham Road]],<br />[[Fulham]]<br />London,<br />England,<br />SW6 1HS
| opened = 28 April 1877<ref name="stadium"/>
| renovated = 1904–1905, 1990s
| owner = [[Chelsea Pitch Owners|Chelsea Pitch Owners plc]]
| operator = Chelsea F.C.
| architect = [[Archibald Leitch]] (1887)
| tenants = London Athletics Club (1877–1904)<br />Chelsea F.C. (1905–present)
| seating_capacity = 41,837-seat<ref name="capacity"/>
| dimensions = 103 x 67&nbsp;metres (112.6 x 73.3&nbsp;yards)<ref name="capacity"/>
}}
Chelsea have only ever had one home ground, Stamford Bridge, where they have played since foundation. It was officially opened on 28 April 1877 and for the first 28 years of its existence it was used almost exclusively by the London Athletics Club as an arena for athletics meetings and not at all for football. In 1904 the ground was acquired by businessman [[Gus Mears]] and his brother [[Joseph Mears|Joseph]], who had also purchased nearby land (formerly a large market garden) with the aim of staging football matches on the now 12.5&nbsp;acre (51,000&nbsp;m²) site.<ref name = "stadium"/> Stamford Bridge was designed for the Mears family by the noted football architect [[Archibald Leitch]], who had also designed [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]], [[Celtic Park]] and [[Hampden Park]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=69–71}}</ref> Most football clubs were founded first, and then sought grounds in which to play, but Chelsea were founded for Stamford Bridge.

Starting with an open bowl-like design and one covered terrace, Stamford Bridge had an original capacity of around 100,000.<ref name = "stadium"/> The early 1930s saw the construction of a terrace on the southern part of the ground with a roof that covered around one fifth of the stand. It eventually became known as the "Shed End", the home of Chelsea's most loyal and vocal supporters, particularly during the 1960s, 70s and 80s. The exact origins of the name are unclear, but the fact that the roof looked like a corrugated iron shed roof played a part.<ref name="stadium">{{cite web
| url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/StadiumHistory/0,,10268,00.html
| title=Stadium History – Introduction
| work=Chelsea F.C. official website
| accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref>

In the early 1970s the club's owners announced a modernisation of Stamford Bridge with plans for a state-of-the-art 50,000 all-seater stadium.<ref name="stadium"/> Work began on the East Stand in 1972 but the project was beset with problems and was never completed; the cost brought the club close to bankruptcy, culminating in the [[Fee simple|freehold]] being sold to property developers. Following a long legal battle, it was not until the mid-1990s that Chelsea's future at the stadium was secured and renovation work resumed.<ref name="stadium"/> The north, west and southern parts of the ground were converted into all-seater stands and moved closer to the pitch, a process completed by 2001.

When Stamford Bridge was redeveloped in the [[Ken Bates]] era many additional features were added to the complex including two hotels, apartments, bars, restaurants, the Chelsea Megastore, and an interactive visitor attraction called Chelsea World of Sport. The intention was that these facilities would provide extra revenue to support the football side of the business, but they were less successful than hoped and before the Abramovich takeover in 2003 the debt taken on to finance them was a major burden on the club. Soon after the takeover a decision was taken to drop the "Chelsea Village" brand and refocus on Chelsea as a football club. However, the stadium is sometimes still referred to as part of ''"Chelsea Village"'' or ''"The Village"''.
[[File:Chelsea-ilkmac.jpg|left|frame|Chelsea ''vs.'' [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] at Stamford Bridge on 23 September 1905; Chelsea won 1–0.]]
The Stamford Bridge [[Freehold (law)|freehold]], the [[Association football pitch|pitch]], the turnstiles and Chelsea's [[naming rights]] are now owned by [[Chelsea Pitch Owners]], a non-profit organisation in which fans are the shareholders. The CPO was created to ensure the stadium could never again be sold to developers. As a condition for using the Chelsea FC name, the club has to play its first team matches at Stamford Bridge, which means that if the club moves to a new stadium, they may have to change their name.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=91–92}}</ref>
Chelsea's [[Cobham Training Centre|training ground]] is located in [[Cobham, Surrey]]. Chelsea moved to Cobham in 2004. Their previous training ground in [[Harlington, London|Harlington]] was taken over by [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |title=QPR take over Chelsea training ground |first=Wayne |last=Veysey |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/article-18829718-qpr-take-over-chelsea-training-ground.do |work=Evening Standard |date=24 May 2005 |accessdate=24 June 2009 }}</ref> The new training facilities in Cobham were completed in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea's new training ground for the future |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/london/content/articles/2007/07/05/chelsea_ground_feature.shtml |work=BBC London |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 July 2007 |accessdate=24 June 2009 }}</ref>

Stamford Bridge has been used for a variety of other sporting events since 1905. It hosted the [[FA Cup Final]] from 1920 to 1922,<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/CupFinalResults
| title=Cup Final Statistics
| work=The Football Association
| accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> has held ten [[FA Cup Semi-finals|FA Cup semi-finals]] (most recently in [[1977–78 FA Cup|1978]]), ten [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] matches (the last in [[1970 FA Charity Shield|1970]]), and three [[England national football team|England international]] matches, the last in 1932; it was also the venue for an unofficial ''Victory International'' in 1946.<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslUnoff.html
| title=England's Matches: Unofficial
| work=Englandfootballonline
| accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> [[File:West Stand Champions.jpg|thumb|230px|right|View from the [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)#West Stand|West Stand]] of [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] during a [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League game]], 2008]] In October 1905 it hosted a [[rugby union]] match between the [[The Original All Blacks|All Blacks]] and Middlesex,<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/allblacks.html
| title=All Blacks
| work=Rugbyfootballhistory.com
| accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> and in 1914 hosted a baseball match between the touring [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]] and the [[Chicago White Sox]].<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.baseballgb.co.uk/?p=9582
| title=Countdown to SABR Day 2011
| work=BaseballGB.co.uk
| accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> It was the venue for a [[boxing]] match between world [[flyweight]] champion [[Jimmy Wilde]] and Joe Conn in 1918.<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/casey/MC_Wilde.htm
| title=Jimmy Wilde: The Original Explosive Thin Man
| work=Cyberboxingzone.com
| accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> The running track was used for [[dirt track racing]] between 1928 and 1932,<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.guskuhn.net/GKuhn/Stamford%20Bridge/StamfordBrdgIndex.htm
| title=Stamford Bridge Speedway
| work=guskuhn.net
| accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> [[greyhound racing]] from 1933 to 1968, and [[Midget car racing]] in 1948.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.speedcarworld.com.au/default.asp?Page=Release&Id=8958| title=U.S. Invades England 1948|work=speedcarworld.com| accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> In 1980, Stamford Bridge hosted the first international [[Floodlights (sport)|floodlit]] [[cricket]] match in the UK, between [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]] and the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]].<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.spincricket.com/tag/invention-of-twenty20/
| title=Twenty20 before Twenty20
| work=spincricket.com
| accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> It was also the home stadium of the [[London Monarchs]] [[American Football]] team for the [[1997 London Monarchs season|1997 season]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.britballnow.co.uk/History/Britball%20Teams/LONDONMONARCHS.htm| title=London Monarchs|work=Britballnow.co.uk| accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref>
The current club ownership have stated that a larger stadium is necessary in order for Chelsea to stay competitive with rival clubs who have significantly larger stadia, such as Arsenal and Manchester United.<ref>{{cite news
 | date = 25 April 2012
 | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17839225
 | title = Chelsea chief: We will drop out of Europe's elite without new stadium
 |publisher=BBC
 | accessdate =6 May 2012}}</ref> Owing to its location next to a main road and two railway lines, fans can only enter the ground via the [[Fulham Road]] exits, which places constraints on expansion due to [[Occupational safety and health|health and safety]] regulations.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=76 }}</ref> The club have consistently affirmed their desire to keep Chelsea at their current home,<ref>{{cite news
 | date = 12 April 2006
 | url = http://www.rte.ie/sport/2006/0412/stamfordbridge.html?rss
 | title = Kenyon confirms Blues will stay at Stamford Bridge
 | publisher=RTÉ Sport
 | accessdate =1 January 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
 | date = 9 November 2008
 | url = http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10268~1448876,00.html
 | title = Observer Stadium Story Denied
 | publisher=Chelsea F.C. official website
 | accessdate =19 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
 | date = 10 November 2010
 | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1328071/Chelsea-deny-Earls-Court-ditch-Stamford-Bridge.html
 | title = Chelsea deny they're to ditch Stamford Bridge for 60,000 stadium at Earls Court
 |work=Daily Mail |location=UK | accessdate =19 March 2011}}</ref> but Chelsea have nonetheless been linked with a move to various nearby sites, including the [[Earls Court Exhibition Centre]], [[Battersea Power Station]] and the [[Chelsea Barracks]].<ref>{{cite news
 | date = 20 January 2006
 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4630618.stm
 | title = Chelsea plan Bridge redevelopment
 |work=BBC Sport
 |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation
 | accessdate =1 January 2007
 }}</ref> On 3 October 2011, Chelsea made a proposal to CPO shareholders to buy back the freehold to the land on which Stamford Bridge sits, stating that "buying back the freehold removes a potential hurdle should a suitable site become available in the future".<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10268~2471443,00.html
| title=Chelsea FC Proposal To Chelsea Pitch Owners
| work=Chelsea F.C. official website
| accessdate=3 October 2011}}</ref> The proposal was voted down by CPO shareholders.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-15481301|title=Chelsea FC lose fan vote on stadium|publisher=BBC|date=27 October 2011|first=Dominic|accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref> In May 2012, the club made a formal bid to purchase Battersea Power Station, with a view to developing the site into a 60,000 seater stadium,<ref>{{cite news
 | date = 4 May 2012
 | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2012/may/04/chelsea-battersea-power-station-stadium?newsfeed=true
 | title = Chelsea bid to buy Battersea power station in £1bn stadium plan
 |work=The Guardian |location=UK | accessdate =6 May 2012}}</ref> but lost out to a Malaysian consortium.<ref>{{cite news
 | date = 5 July 2012
 | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2012/jul/05/chelsea-battersea-malaysian-consortium
 | title = Chelsea's Battersea hopes end as Malaysian consortium completes deal
 |work=The Guardian |location=UK | accessdate =10 November 2012}}</ref>

==Crest and colours==

===Crest===
Since the club's foundation, Chelsea have had four main crests, though all underwent minor variations. In 1905, Chelsea adopted as their first crest the image of a [[Chelsea pensioner]], which contributed to the "pensioner" nickname, and remained for the next half-century, though it never appeared on the shirts. As part of [[Ted Drake]]'s modernisation of the club from 1952 onwards, he insisted that the pensioner badge be removed from the match day programme to change the club's image and that a new crest be adopted.<ref name="crests">{{cite web
| url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/HistoryDetail/0,,10268~1328582,00.html
| title=Club Badges
| work=Chelsea F.C. official website
| accessdate =24 January 2012}}</ref> As a stop-gap, a temporary emblem comprising simply the initials C.F.C. was adopted for one year.
In 1953, Chelsea's crest was changed to an upright blue lion looking backwards and holding a [[crosier|staff]], which was to endure for the next three decades. This crest was based on elements in the [[coat of arms]] of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Chelsea]]<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.civicheraldry.co.uk/lcc.html#chelsea%20bc
| title=Chelsea Metropolitan Borough Council
| work=Civic Heraldry of England and Wales
| accessdate = 21 January 2007}}</ref> with the "lion rampant regardant" taken from the arms of then club president [[Earl Cadogan|Viscount Chelsea]] and the staff from the [[Westminster Abbey|Abbots of Westminster]], former Lords of the Manor of Chelsea. It also featured three red roses, to represent England, and two footballs. This was the first club badge to appear on shirts, since the policy of putting the crest on the shirts was only adopted in the early 1960s.<ref name="crests"/>

In 1986, with [[Ken Bates]] now owner of the club, Chelsea's crest was changed again as part of another attempt to modernise and to capitalise on new marketing opportunities.<ref name="crests"/> The new badge featured a more naturalistic non-heraldic lion, in white and not blue, standing over the C.F.C. initials. It lasted for the next 19 years, with some modifications such as the use of different colours, including red from 1987 to 1995, and yellow from 1995 until 1999, before the white returned.<ref name = "HFK">{{cite web| title = Historical Kits – Chelsea
| url = http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Chelsea/Chelsea.htm
| first = Dave
| last = Moor
| publisher = Historical Kits
| accessdate =28 September 2011}}</ref> With the new ownership of [[Roman Abramovich]], and the club's centenary approaching, combined with demands from fans for the popular 1950s badge to be restored, it was decided that the crest should be changed again in 2005. The new crest was officially adopted for the start of the [[2005–06 in English football|2005–06]] season and marked a return to the older design, used from 1953 to 1986, featuring a blue heraldic lion holding a staff. For the centenary season this was accompanied by the words '100 YEARS' and 'CENTENARY 2005–2006' on the top and bottom of the crest respectively.<ref name="new crest"/>

<center>
<gallery>
File:Chelsea First Badge.png|Chelsea's crest, 1905–52
File:Chelsea FC 52-53.png|Chelsea's crest, 1952–53
File:Chelsea old logo.png|Chelsea's crest, 1953–86
File:Chelsea Crest 1986-2005.png|Chelsea's crest, 1986–2005
File:Chelsea FC 100th anniversary crest.png|Chelsea's crest, 2005–06, <br />which commemorated Chelsea's 100th anniversary, was used only in the [[2005–06 Chelsea F.C. season|2005–06 season]]
</gallery>
</center>

===Colours===
{{Football kit box
| align = right
| pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=
| pattern_b =
| pattern_ra =
| leftarm = 96C8A2
| body = 96C8A2
| rightarm = 96C8A2
| shorts = FFFFFM
| socks = 191970
| title = Chelsea's first home colours, used from 1905 until c.1912.
}}

Chelsea have always worn blue shirts, although they originally used the paler [[eton blue]], which was taken from the racing colours of then club president, [[Earl Cadogan]], and was worn with white shorts and dark blue or black socks.<ref>{{cite web
 | url = http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Chelsea/Chelsea.htm
 | title= Chelsea – Historical Football Kits
 | work=Historical Kits
 | accessdate =26 June 2012
 }}</ref> The light blue shirts were replaced by a royal blue version in around 1912.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill, Rick | title=Chelsea Football Club: The Official History in Pictures| year=2006| isbn=0-7553-1467-0}} p. 212</ref> In the 1960s Chelsea manager [[Tommy Docherty]] changed the kit again, switching to blue shorts (which have remained ever since) and white socks, believing it made the club's colours more modern and distinctive, since no other major side used that combination; this kit was first worn during the 1964–65 season.<ref>{{cite book | author=Mears, Brian | title=Chelsea: Football Under the Blue Flag| publisher=Mainstream Sport| year=2002| isbn=1-84018-658-5 | page=42 }}</ref> Since then Chelsea have always worn white socks with their home kit apart from a short spell from 1985 to 1992, when blue socks were reintroduced.

Chelsea's traditional away colours are all yellow or all white with blue trim, but, as with most teams, they have had some more unusual ones. The first away strip consisted of black and white stripes and for one game in the 1960s the team wore blue and black stripes, inspired by [[Inter Milan]]'s kit, again at Docherty's behest.<ref>The "Inter Milan" kit was worn for an FA Cup semi-final against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], on 23 April 1966. Reference: Mears (2002), p. 58</ref> Other memorable away kits include a mint green strip in the 1980s, a red and white checked one in the early 90s and a graphite and tangerine edition in the mid-1990s.<ref>{{cite web
 | url = http://www.chelseafc.com/xxchelsea180706/index.html#/page/ClassicKits
 | title= Kits
 | work=Chelsea F.C. official website
 | accessdate =1 January 2007
 }}</ref>

==Support==
[[File:Chelsea defend corner.jpg|thumb|250px|Chelsea fans at a match against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], on 11 March 2006]]
Chelsea have the fifth highest average all-time attendance in [[Football in England|English football]]<ref name="attendance"/> and regularly attract over 40,000 fans to Stamford Bridge; they were the sixth best-supported [[Premier League]] team in the 2012–13 season, with an average gate of 41,462.<ref name="12/13 attendances"/> Chelsea's traditional fanbase comes from all over the [[Greater London]] area including working-class parts such as [[Hammersmith]] and [[Battersea]], wealthier areas like Chelsea and [[Kensington]], and from the [[home counties]]. There are also numerous official supporters clubs in the United Kingdom and all over the world.<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/SupporterClubsMap/0,,10268,00.html
| title=Supporters Clubs Map
| work= Chelsea F.C. official website
| accessdate=21 February 2011}}</ref> Between 2007 and 2012 Chelsea were ranked fourth worldwide in annual replica kit sales, with an average of 910,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=EXCLUSIVE: Manchester United and Real Madrid top global shirt sale charts |url=http://www.sportingintelligence.com/2012/10/08/exclusive-manchester-united-and-real-madrid-top-global-shirt-sale-charts-081001/ |work=Sporting Intelligence|date=8 October 2012 |accessdate=8 October 2012}}</ref>

At matches, Chelsea fans sing [[football chants|chants]] such as ''"[[Carefree (chant)|Carefree]]"'' (to the tune of [[Lord of the Dance (hymn)|Lord of the Dance]], whose lyrics were probably written by supporter Mick Greenaway<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=150}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fanchants.com/football-songs/chelsea-chants/carefree/ |title="Carefree" audio sample |publisher=Fanchants.com |accessdate=3 September 2011}}</ref>), ''"Ten Men Went to Mow"'', ''"We All Follow the Chelsea"'' (to the tune of "[[Land of Hope and Glory]]"), ''"Zigga Zagga"'', and the celebratory ''"Celery"'', with the latter often resulting in fans ritually throwing celery. The vegetable was banned inside Stamford Bridge after an incident involving [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]] midfielder [[Cesc Fàbregas]] at the [[2007 Football League Cup Final|2007 League Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news
| date=17 April 2002
| url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,1563,685859,00.html
| title=Fans sent spinning after tossing salad |work=The Guardian
| accessdate=1 January 2007
| author=Scott Murray}}</ref>
[[File:Chelsea-Pub-Taschkent.JPG|right|thumb|150px|Mural at a Chelsea pub in [[Tashkent]]]]
During the 1970s and 1980s in particular, Chelsea supporters were associated with [[Football (soccer) hooliganism|football hooliganism]]. The club's "[[Football hooliganism|football firm]]", originally known as the Chelsea Shed Boys, and subsequently as the [[Chelsea Headhunters]], were nationally notorious for football violence, alongside hooligan firms from other clubs such as [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]'s [[Inter City Firm]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]'s [[Millwall Bushwackers|Bushwackers]], before, during and after matches.<ref>{{cite news
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/hooligans/1962503.stm
| title=Making a new start
| work=BBC News
| accessdate=21 January 2007
  | date=2 May 2002}}</ref> The increase of hooligan incidents in the 1980s led chairman Ken Bates to propose erecting an electric fence to deter them from invading the pitch, a proposal that the [[Greater London Council]] rejected.<ref>{{cite news
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/3037508.stm
| title=Bates: Chelsea's driving force
| work=BBC Sport
| publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation
| accessdate = 21 January 2007 | date=2 July 2003}}</ref>

Since the 1990s there has been a marked decline in crowd trouble at matches, as a result of stricter policing, [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]] in grounds and the advent of [[All-seater stadium|all-seater stadia]].<ref>{{cite news |date=2 June 1998 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1998/hooligans/60146.stm | title=Soccer hooliganism: Made in England, but big abroad |publisher=BBC News | accessdate=1 January 2007}}</ref> In 2007, the club launched the [[Back to the Shed campaign|'Back to the Shed' campaign]] to improve the atmosphere at home matches, with notable success. According to [[Home Office]] statistics, 126 Chelsea fans were arrested for football-related offences during the [[2009–10 in English football|2009–10]] season, the third highest in the division, and 27 [[banning order]]s were issued, the fifth highest in the division.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/crime/football-arrests-banning-orders/fbo-2009-10?view=Binary |title=Statistics on football-related arrests and banning orders |accessdate=14 May 2011 |month=November |year=2010 |publisher=Home Office|format = PDF}}</ref>

===Rivalries===
{{Main|West London derby|Arsenal F.C.–Chelsea F.C. rivalry|Chelsea F.C.–Leeds United A.F.C. rivalry}}
Chelsea do not have a traditional rivalry on the scale of the [[Merseyside derby]] or the [[North London derby]] because their [[West London derby|West London derbies]] with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] or [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] have not been as prominent over the years since the clubs have often been in different divisions. A 2004 survey by Planetfootball.com found that Chelsea fans consider their main rivalries to be with (in order): Arsenal, [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.thefootballnetwork.net/main/s120/st44186.htm
| title=Football Rivalries: The Complete Results
| work=Planetfootball.com
| accessdate=2 January 2007
 }}</ref> Their rivalry with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] is said to have developed following the [[1967 FA Cup Final]], the first cup final held between two London clubs. Additionally, a [[Chelsea F.C.–Leeds United A.F.C. rivalry|strong rivalry]] with [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] dates back to several heated and controversial matches in the 1960s and 1970s, particularly the [[1970 FA Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=321–325}}</ref> More recently a rivalry with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] has grown following repeated clashes in cup competitions.<ref>{{cite news
| url=http://www.talksport.co.uk/magazine/features/2011-05-19/peterborough-v-mk-dons-liverpool-v-chelsea-stoke-v-cardiff-six-best-modern-football-rivalries
| title=Six very modern football rivalries
| work=TalkSport
| accessdate=23 May 2011
  | date=19 May 2011}}</ref>

==Records==
{{details|List of Chelsea F.C. records and statistics}}
[[File:Lampard playing.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Frank Lampard]] is Chelsea's all-time highest goalscorer]]
Chelsea's highest appearance-maker is ex-captain [[Ron Harris (footballer)|Ron Harris]], who played in 795 first-class games for the club between 1961 and 1980.<ref name="stats">For the appearance and goalscoring records of all Chelsea players, see {{cite book | author=Glanvill | year = 2006 | title = Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages = 399–410 }}</ref> This record is unlikely to be broken in the near future; Chelsea's current highest appearance-maker is [[Frank Lampard]] with 627.<ref name="current player">{{cite web
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/
| title = soccerbase.com | accessdate = 13 December 2009 }}</ref> The record for a Chelsea goalkeeper is held by Harris's contemporary, [[Peter Bonetti]], who made 729 appearances (1959–79). With 103 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] (101 while at the club), Frank Lampard of England is Chelsea's most capped international player.

Frank Lampard is Chelsea's all-time top goalscorer, with 207 goals in 627 games (2001–);<ref name="stats"/> he passed [[Bobby Tambling]]'s longstanding record of 202 in May 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22589526 | title = Chelsea's Frank Lampard given golden boot by Bobby Tambling | publisher=BBC | date = 19 May 2013 | accessdate = 7 September 2013 }}</ref> Seven other players have also scored over 100 goals for Chelsea: [[George Hilsdon]] (1906–12), [[George Mills (footballer)|George Mills]] (1929–39), [[Roy Bentley]] (1948–56), [[Jimmy Greaves]] (1957–61), [[Peter Osgood]] (1964–74 and 1978–79), [[Kerry Dixon]] (1983–92) and [[Didier Drogba]] (2004–12). Greaves holds the record for the most goals scored in one season (43 in 1960–61).<ref name="current player"/>

Chelsea's biggest winning scoreline in a competitive match is 13–0, achieved against [[Jeunesse Hautcharage]] in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] in 1971.<ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10268~2465594,00.html
| title = Words on Winning: 21–0
| work = Chelsea F.C. official website
| accessdate = 15 January 2012 }}</ref> The club's biggest top-flight win was an 8–0 victory against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in 2010, and matched in 2012 against Aston Villa.<ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.chelseafc.com/matchreport/20100509/chelsea-8-wigan-0_2249014_47531
| title = Chelsea v Wigan match report
| work = Chelsea F.C. official website
| accessdate = 15 January 2012 }}</ref> Chelsea's biggest loss was an 8–1 reverse against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in 1953.<ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=52914/profile/index.html
| title = Chelsea F.C.
| work = Union of European Football Associations
| accessdate = 15 January 2012 }}</ref> Officially, Chelsea's highest home attendance is 82,905 for a [[Football League First Division|First Division]] match against Arsenal on 12 October 1935. However, an estimated crowd of over 100,000 attended a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]] against [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] team [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]] on 13 November 1945.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/TeamHistory/0,,10268~1800268,00.html |title=Team History – 1940s |publisher=Chelsea F.C. official website |accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Brian Viner: Diamond days of side who brought touch of glamour to post-war Britain |first=Brian |last=Viner |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/brian-viner-diamond-days-of-side-who-brought-touch-of-glamour-to-postwar-britain-6143279.html |work=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=29 October 2005 |accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref> The modernisation of Stamford Bridge during the 1990s and the introduction of all-seater stands mean that neither record will be broken for the foreseeable future. The current legal capacity of Stamford Bridge is 41,837.<ref name="capacity"/>

Chelsea hold the English record for the highest ever points total for a league season (95), the fewest goals conceded during a league season (15), the highest number of Premier League victories in a season (29), the highest number of clean sheets overall in a Premier League season (25) (all set during the [[FA Premier League 2004-05|2004–05 season]]),<ref name="records">{{cite news
| date=13 May 2005
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4545045.stm
| title=Mourinho proud of battling finish |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation accessdate=29 August 2010
}}</ref> and the most consecutive clean sheets from the start of a league season (6, set during the [[2005–06 FA Premier League|2005–06 season]]).<ref>{{cite news
| date=17 September 2005
| title=Charlton 0–2 Chelsea
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4232354.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation
| accessdate=12 November 2007 }}</ref> The club's 21–0 [[Playoff format#Total points series (aggregate)|aggregate]] victory over [[UN Käerjéng 97|Jeunesse Hautcharage]] in the [[1971–72 European Cup Winners' Cup|UEFA Cup Winners' Cup in 1971]] remains a record in European competition.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/cwc.html#rec
| title=Cup Winners' Cup Trivia
| work=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation
| accessdate = 21 January 2007}}</ref> Chelsea hold the record for the longest streak of unbeaten matches at home in the English top-flight, which lasted 86 matches from 20 March 2004 to 26 October 2008. They secured the record on 12 August 2007, beating the previous record of 63 matches unbeaten set by Liverpool between 1978 and 1980.<ref>{{cite news
| date=12 August 2007
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6931067.stm
| title=Chelsea 3–2 Birmingham |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation
| accessdate=9 October 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7674108.stm|title=Chelsea 0–1 Liverpool|work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate =26 October 2008 | date=26 October 2008}}</ref> Chelsea's streak of eleven consecutive away league wins, set between 5 April 2008 and 6 December 2008, is also a record for the English top flight.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea in eleven heaven |url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/Magazinedettail/0,,12306~1491763,00.html |work=Premier League |date=8 December 2008 |accessdate =18 January 2009 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20081219192857/http://www.premierleague.com/page/Magazinedettail/0,,12306~1491763,00.html |archivedate=19 December 2008 }}</ref> Their £50m purchase of [[Fernando Torres]] in January 2011 is a [[Progression of British football transfer fee record|British record transfer fee]].<ref>{{cite news
| date=31 January 2011
| title=Torres makes record move from Liverpool to Chelsea
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/9380389.stm |work=BBC
| accessdate=12 March 2012 }}</ref>

Chelsea, along with Arsenal, were the first club to play with shirt numbers, on 25 August 1928 in their match against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea Town]].<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamUnif/UnifNosNames.html
| title=Shirt Numbers
| work=England Football Online
| accessdate = 1 October 2006 }}</ref> They were the first English side to travel by aeroplane to a domestic away match, when they visited [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 19 April 1957,<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=96}}</ref> and the first First Division side to play a match on a Sunday, when they faced [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on 27 January 1974. On 26 December 1999, Chelsea became the first British side to field an entirely foreign [[starting line-up]] (no British or Irish players) in a Premier League match against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news
| date=27 December 1999
| url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/premiership/chelsea/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/99/12/26/SOCCER_Southampton_Nightlead.html&TEAMHD=chelsea&DIV=prem&TEAM=CHELSEA&RH=Chelsea&PREV_SEASON=1998
| title=Southampton 1 Chelsea 2
| work=Sporting Life
| accessdate=27 January 2007
| author=Bradley, Mark}}</ref> On 19 May 2007, they became the first team to win the FA Cup at the new [[Wembley Stadium]], having also been the last to win it at the old Wembley.<ref>{{cite news
| date=20 May 2007
| title=Something old, new and Blue
| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/blog/2007/may/19/somethingoldnewandblue |work=The Observer
| accessdate=14 July 2011
| author=Mitchell, Kevin}}</ref> At the end of the 2007–08 season, Chelsea became the highest ranked club under [[UEFA coefficient|UEFA's five-year coefficient]] system, the first English club to do so in the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.xs4all.nl/~kassiesa/bert/uefa/data/method3/trank2008.html
| title=UEFA Team Ranking 2008
| work=UEFA European Cup Football: Results and Qualification
| author=Kassies, Bert
| accessdate = 2 June 2008 }}</ref> On the final day of the 2009–10 season, Chelsea became the first team in Premier League history to score at least 100 goals in a single season.<ref name=Wigan80/> In 2012, Chelsea became the first London based club to win the [[UEFA Champions League]], after beating Bayern Munich in the [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final|final]].<ref name="Chelsea win breaks London duck"/><ref name="Chelsea etch new name on trophy">{{cite news |title=Chelsea etch new name on trophy |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1798280.html#chelsea+etch+name+trophy |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=19 May 2012 |accessdate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> On winning the [[2012–13 UEFA Europa League]], Chelsea became the first English club to [[European football records|win all four European trophies]].

==Ownership and finances==
[[File:Roman Abramovich 2.jpg|thumb|150px|Chelsea owner [[Roman Abramovich]]]]
Chelsea Football Club was founded by [[Gus Mears]] in 1905. After his death in 1912, his descendents continued to own the club until 1982, when [[Ken Bates]] bought the club from Mears' great-nephew [[Brian Mears]] for £1. Bates bought a controlling stake in the club and floated Chelsea on the [[Alternative Investment Market|AIM]] stock exchange in March 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Football Clubs on the UK Stock Markets |url=http://www.footballeconomy.com/stats/stats_turnover_09.htm |publisher=Football Economy |accessdate=26 June 2012}}</ref> In July 2003, [[Roman Abramovich]] purchased just over 50% of Chelsea Village plc's share capital, including Bates' 29.5% stake, for £30&nbsp;million and over the following weeks bought out most of the remaining 12,000 shareholders at 35 pence per share, completing a £140&nbsp;million takeover. Other shareholders at the time of the takeover included the [[Matthew Harding]] estate (21%), [[BSkyB]] (9.9%) and various anonymous offshore trusts.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea tycoon to clear club's debt |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2406994/Bates-sells-off-Chelsea-to-a-Russian-billionaire.html |publisher=The Telegraph|date=7 February 2003 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> After passing the 90% share threshold, Abramovich took the club back into private hands, delisting it from the AIM on 22 August 2003. He also took on responsibility for the club's debt of £80 million, quickly paying most of it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea tycoon to clear club's debt |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3102819.stm |publisher=BBC|date=28 July 2003 |accessdate=26 June 2012}}</ref>

Thereafter, Abramovich changed the ownership name to Chelsea FC plc, whose ultimate parent company is Fordstam Limited, which is controlled by him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Club Information|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/ClubInfo/0,,10268,00.html |publisher=Chelseafc.com |accessdate=26 June 2012}}</ref> Chelsea are additionally funded by Abramovich via interest free [[soft loan]]s channelled through his holding company Fordstam Limited. The loans stood at £709 million in December 2009, when they were all converted to [[Equity (finance)|equity]] by Abramovich, leaving the club itself debt free,<ref>{{cite news |title=Roman Abramovich turns £340m of debt into equity as Chelsea loss falls |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/dec/30/roman-abramovich-chelsea-debts-accounts |work=The Guardian|date=30 December 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Statement on Club Finance|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10268~2055740,00.html |publisher=Chelseafc.com |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> although the debt remains with Fordstam.<ref>{{cite news |title=Roman Abramovich still owed £726m under complex Chelsea structure |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2010/may/19/roman-abramovich-chelsea-loan-debt |work=The Guardian|date=19 May 2010 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> Since 2008 the club has had no external debt.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea and United debts at record £1.5bn |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2008/may/20/premierleague.chelsea |work=The Guardian|date=20 May 2008 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> In November 2012, Chelsea announced a profit of £1.4 million for the year ending 30 June 2012, the first time the club has made a profit under Abramovich's ownership.<ref>{{cite news |title=CHELSEA FC ANNOUNCES ANNUAL PROFIT |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/2975285/title/chelsea-fc-announces-annual-profit |work=Chelsea F.C.|date=9 November 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea FC record first Abramovich-era profit |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/20270934 |work=BBC|date=9 November 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>

Chelsea has been described as a global brand; a 2012 report by [[Brand Finance]] ranked Chelsea fifth and valued the club's brand value at US $398&nbsp;million – an increase of 27% from the previous year, also valuing it at US $10&nbsp;million more than the sixth best brand, London rivals Arsenal – and gave the brand a strength rating of AA (very strong).<ref>{{cite web |title=Top 20 most Valuable Football Club Brands |url=http://www.brandfinance.com/images/upload/top_30_european_football_brands_2011_final_website.pdf |publisher=Brand Finance |accessdate=26 June 2012 |month=May |year=2012 |format=PDF }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Top 30 Football Club Brands |url=http://www.brandfinance.com/images/upload/brandfinance_football_brands_2012.pdf |publisher=Brand Finance |accessdate=4 October 2011 |month=September |year=2011 |format=PDF }}</ref> In 2012, [[Forbes]] magazine ranked Chelsea seventh in their list of the ten most valuable football clubs in the world, valuing the club's brand at £473&nbsp;million ($761&nbsp;million).<ref name="Forbes List"/><ref name="BBC - Forbes"/> Chelsea are currently ranked sixth in the [[Deloitte Football Money League]]<ref name="Deloitte_money_league">{{cite news |title=Chelsea – Deloitte Football Money League 2012  |url=http://www.deloitte.com/assets/Dcom-Sweden/Local%20Assets/Documents/FootballMoneyLeague%202012-uk-sbg-dfml-2012-final120209.pdf |work=Deloitte |accessdate=26 June 2010 }}</ref> with an annual commercial revenue of £225.6&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fan power Football Money League |url=http://www.deloitte.com/view/en_GB/uk/industries/sportsbusinessgroup/sports/football/deloitte-football-money-league-2011/96bd3d3d32245310VgnVCM1000001a56f00aRCRD.htm |work=Deloitte |accessdate=26 June 2012 }}</ref>
[[File:Sergio Perez 2012 Canadian GP - Crop.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Sauber|Sauber F1 Team]], an official partner of the club, displaying the Chelsea FC crest]]

Chelsea's kit has been manufactured by [[Adidas]] since 2006, which is contracted to supply the club's kit from 2006 to 2018. The partnership was extended in October 2010 in a deal worth £160 million over eight years.<ref>{{cite news |date=22 October 2010 |title=Chelsea manager Carlo Ancelotti puts his faith in elder statesman Didier Drogba
| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/8081823/Chelsea-manager-Carlo-Ancelotti-puts-his-faith-in-elder-statesman-Didier-Drogba.html | publisher=The Telegraph| accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> This deal was again extended in June 2013 in a deal worth £300 million over another ten years.<ref>{{cite news |date=22 June 2013 |title=Chelsea agree whopping £300m kit deal with sportswear giants adidas
| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2346083/Chelsea-agree-record-300m-kit-deal-sportswear-giants-adidas.html | publisher=Daily mail| accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=22 June 2013 |title=CHELSEA AND ADIDAS ANNOUNCE EXTENSION OF GLOBAL PARTNERSHIP
| url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3216081/title/chelsea-and-adidas-announce-extension-of-global-partnership | publisher=Chelsea FC| accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref> Previously, the kit was manufactured by [[Umbro]] (1968–81), [[Le Coq Sportif]] (1981–86), The Chelsea Collection (1986–87) and Umbro again (1987–2006). Chelsea's first shirt sponsor was [[Gulf Air]], agreed during the 1983–84 season. The club were then sponsored by Grange Farms, [[Peter Foster|Bai Lin Tea]] and [[Simod]] before a long-term deal was signed with [[Commodore International]] in 1989; [[Amiga]], an off-shoot of Commodore, also appeared on the shirts. Chelsea were subsequently sponsored by [[Coors Brewing Company|Coors]] beer (1995–97), [[Autoglass]] (1997–2001) and [[Emirates Airline]] (2001–05). Chelsea's current shirt sponsor is [[Samsung Group|Samsung]] who took over the sponsorship from their mobile division in 2007–08.<ref>{{cite news |date=2 May 2005 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article387503.ece|title=Clubs to cash in on mobile advertising |work=The Times | location=UK | accessdate=21 January 2010 | author=Ashling O'Connor}}</ref> In 2012 [[Gazprom]] became the club's official Global Energy Partner on a three-year sponsorship deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/chelsea-article/article/2852061/title/gazprom |title=Sponsors & Partners – GAZPROM |publisher=Chelsea F.C. official website}}</ref> The club also has a variety of other sponsors and partners, which include [[Delta Air Lines]],<ref>[http://finance.yahoo.com/news/delta-chelsea-football-club-strike-120000415.html Delta and Chelsea Football Club Strike Sponsorship Deal – Yahoo! Finance]</ref> [[Sauber]], [[Audi]], [[Singha]], [[EA Sports]], [[Dolce & Gabbana]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG7913107/Dolce-and-Gabbana-and-Chelsea-Football-Club.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana and Chelsea Football Club |publisher=Telegraph |date=27 July 2010}}</ref> Barbados Tourism Authority, [[Atlas Group|Atlas]], [[AZIMUT Hotels Company|AZIMUT Hotels]], [[Bank Negara Indonesia|BNI]], [[Vietinbank]], [[Toyo Tire & Rubber Company|Nitto Tire]], Orico, [[Guangzhou R&F F.C.|Guangzhou R&F]], [[Coca Cola]], Grand Royal, [[Digicel]], [[Lucozade Sport]], and [[Viagogo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/SponsorsAndPartnersIndex|title=Sponsors and Partners |publisher=Chelsea F.C. official website|accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>

==Chelsea Ladies==
{{details|Chelsea L.F.C.}}
Chelsea also operate a [[Women's association football|women's football]] team, [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea Ladies]]. It has been affiliated to the men's team since 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalesoccer.net/show_news_article.php?id=3523|title=Chelsea Moving on Up|publisher=FemaleSoccer.net|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> and is part of the club's Community Development programme. They play their home games at [[Imperial Fields]], the home ground of [[Isthmian League Premier Division|Isthmian League]] club [[Tooting & Mitcham United F.C.|Tooting & Mitcham United]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LadiesNews/0,,10268~2117196,00.html | title=About the Ladies |work=Chelsea F.C. official website | accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> The club won the Surrey County Cup in 2003, 2004, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009 and 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surreyfa.com/FixturesAndResults/previouswinners/Womens.htm|title=Womens Cup|publisher=surreyfa.com|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> and were promoted to the [[FA Women's Premier League National Division|Premier Division]] for the first time in 2005 as [[FA Women's Premier League Southern Division|Southern Division]] champions. In the [[2009–10 FA Women's Premier League|2009–10]] season, they finished 3rd in the Premier League, equalling their highest ever placing, and in 2010 were one of the eight founder members of the [[FA WSL|FA Women's Super League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbusiness.co.uk/news/article/newsitem=195/title=eight+teams+successful+in+women%26%23039%3Bs+super+league+bid|title=Eight teams successful in Women's Super League bid|publisher=fcbusiness.co.uk|accessdate=20 February 2011 | location=London | date=24 March 2010}}</ref> [[John Terry]], the current captain of the Chelsea men's team, is President of Chelsea LFC.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/oct/18/john-terry-chelsea-womens-football|title=John Terry digs deep to rescue Chelsea Ladies after funding cuts|work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=20 February 2011  | first=Tony | last=Leighton | date=18 October 2009}}</ref>

==Popular culture==
[[File:Chelsea double winner 2009-10.JPG|left|thumb|200px|Chelsea parade through the streets of Fulham and Chelsea after winning their league and cup double, May 2010]]
In 1930, Chelsea featured in one of the earliest football films, ''[[The Great Game (1930 film)|The Great Game]]''.<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0020936/
| title=The Great Game
| work=IMDb
| accessdate = 1 October 2007 }}</ref> One-time Chelsea centre forward, [[Jack Cock]], who by then was playing for [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], was the star of the film and several scenes were shot at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], including the pitch, the boardroom, and the [[dressing room]]s. It included guest appearances by then-Chelsea players [[Andrew Nesbit Wilson|Andrew Wilson]], [[George Mills (footballer)|George Mills]], and [[Sam Millington]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=120–121}}</ref> Owing to the notoriety of the [[Chelsea Headhunters]], a [[football firm]] associated with the club, Chelsea have also featured in films about football [[hooliganism]], including 2004's ''[[The Football Factory (film)|The Football Factory]]''.<ref>{{cite news
| date=10 May 2004
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/3687227.stm
| title=Football firms hit the film circuit |publisher=BBC Sport
| accessdate=25 January 2007
| author=Steve Hawkes}}</ref> Chelsea also appear in the [[Hindi]] film ''[[Jhoom Barabar Jhoom]]''.<ref>{{cite news
| date=25 September 2006
| url=http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp?NewsID=1055099
| title=Chelsea teams up with Yash Raj Films
| publisher=DNA India
| accessdate=1 January 2007 }}</ref> In April 2011, [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] comedy series ''Nijesmo mi od juče'' made an episode in which Chelsea plays against [[FK Sutjeska Nikšić]] for qualification of the [[UEFA Champions League]].<ref>[http://www.nijesmomiodjuce.com/nijesmo-mi-od-juce-novosti/epizoda-chelsea-u-gledajte-onlajn-sekciji/ Nijesmo mi od Juce – Novosti – Epizode – Chelsea u "gledajte onlajn" sekciji] Retrieved 27 April 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UQyt0BLwMBI&feature=plcp YouTube – Chelsea – Nijesmo mi od juče]</ref>

Up until the 1950s, the club had a long-running association with the [[music hall]]s, with their underachievement often providing material for comedians such as [[George Robey]].<ref>{{cite news
| date=30 September 2002
| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2002/sep/30/match.sport7
| title=Di Canio has last laugh at Chelsea comedy store |work=The Guardian
| accessdate=14 July 2011
| author=Scott Murray}}</ref> It culminated in comedian Norman Long's release of a [[Novelty song|comic song]] in 1933, ironically titled "On the Day That Chelsea Went and Won the Cup", the lyrics of which describe a series of bizarre and improbable occurrences on the hypothetical day when Chelsea finally won a trophy.<ref name="glanville"/>
The song "[[Blue is the Colour (Chelsea)|Blue is the Colour]]" was released as a single in the build-up to the [[1972 Football League Cup Final|1972 League Cup Final]], with all members of Chelsea's first team squad singing; it reached number five in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.chartstats.com/songinfo.php?id=5791
| title=Blue Is The Colour
| work=Chart Stats
| accessdate = 21 January 2007 }}</ref> (The song was later adopted, as an anthem, by the [[Vancouver Whitecaps (USL)|Vancouver Whitecaps]] in Canada, after being changed to "White is the Colour".<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.vancourier.com/issues02/045202/sports.html
| archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080103163706/http://www.vancourier.com/issues02/045202/sports.html
| archivedate=3 January 2008
| title=Caps' 'Proclaim' season opener
| work=Vancouver Courier
| accessdate = 21 January 2007}}</ref>) In the build-up to the [[FA Cup Final 1997|1997 FA Cup Final]], the song "Blue Day", performed by [[Suggs (singer)|Suggs]] and members of the Chelsea squad, reached number 22 in the UK charts.<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.chartstats.com/songinfo.php?id=25206
| title=Blue Day
| work=Chart Stats
| accessdate = 21 January 2007 }}</ref> [[Bryan Adams]], a fan of Chelsea,<ref>{{cite news
| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/chelsea/article2967989.ece
| title=The soul of Chelsea in 50 moments
| work=Times Online
| date = 29 November 2007}}</ref> dedicated the song "We're Gonna Win" from the album ''[[18 Til I Die]]'' to the club.<ref>{{cite news
| url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/1116450/Countdown-to-the-Champions-League-final-in-Moscow-Who-are-ya.html?offset=2
| title=Countdown to the Champions League Final in Moscow
| work=The Sun
| date = 2 May 2008}}</ref>
{{clear}}

